04821nam a22009015i 9780520919594DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209195947 a10.1525/97805209195942doi  a(DE-B1597)542742  a(OCoLC)1149504750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a111qOCoLC221/eng/202311201 aFritsche, Johannes, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistorical Destiny and National Socialism in Heidegger's Being and Time /cJohannes Fritsche.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (375 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Being and Time, Section 74 -- t2. Being and Time, Sections 72-77 -- t3. Fate, Community, and Society -- t4. Being and Time and Leftist Concepts of History and Decision -- t5. Heidegger after the Machtergreifung -- t6. Epilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere has been much debate over the relationship of Heidegger's philosophy—in particular his book Being and Time—to his practical involvement with National Socialism. Yet the question has never been addressed through a comparison of Being and Time with other texts on history and politics written at the time. Johannes Fritsche does this, providing a detailed interpretation of the relevant passages in Being and Time—especially sections 72-77 on fate, community, and society. He analyzes for comparison two other authors who explicitly regarded themselves as rightists—Adolf Hitler (Mein Kampf) and Max Scheler (Formalism in Ethics and other writings)—and two authors on the left—Georg Lukács (History and Class Consciousness) and Paul Tillich (The Socialist Decision).Fritsche concludes that Being and Time is a brilliant summary of right-wing politics in general, which proposes the destruction of liberal society in order to regenerate an idealized community. In addition, Heidegger rejects positions on the right, such as Scheler's, that enabled their authors to distance themselves from the most extreme political rightists, and thus he paves the way for National Socialism. Being and Time, Fritsche demonstrates, must be seen as a clear case for the National Socialists and their project of revitalization of the Volksgemeinschaft, the community of the people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational socialism and philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aadolf hitler.  abeing and time.  acommunity.  aexistentialism.  afate.  aformalism in ethics.  ageorg lukacs.  agerman philosophy.  aheidegger.  ahistory and class consciousness.  ahistory and politics.  aidealized community.  aleft wing politics.  aleftist politics.  aliberal society.  amartin heidegger.  amax scheler.  ameaning of being.  amein kampf.  ametaphysics.  anational socialism.  apaul tillich.  aphenomenology.  aphilosophy.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitics.  aright wing politics.  arightist politics.  asocialism.  asociety.  athe socialist decision.  avolksgemeinschaft.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021002840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919594?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919594/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles